content.description:
A wondering line featuring several small traversals and technical movements around small arêtes. A real 5.10b, stiffer than most in the area. 



Right of Spruce Root Shute, and first bolted line in Star Trek Sector. Identifiable by budgey orange rock face and the identifier rock at the base reading "Breakfast Cookie 5.10a S".   

Bolted with fixed anchors.

Roof variation of First Flight, adds a punchy bottom to easier slab uptop.



Located in middle of the easy sport climbing wall near the end of the Star Trek Sector. 

Bolted with fixed anchors.

Start below a small roof and climb up, bypassing it to the right before heading left along the base of the second larger roof. Once clear blast up easy slab to the anchors. 

Possible to just sport lead it with a bit of runout between bolts 2 and 3. A single finger/hand sized cam placement will greatly reduce the ground fall potential under the roof.



Located mid wall below and slightly right of a small bolted roof. 

Bolted with fixed anchors.

Mixed line up slightly overhanging rock featuring great movement.



Located centrally in the left section of the main theatre area of the Star Trek Sector. Identifiable by the broken bolted line that is broken up by large rock bulge and horizontal cracks.

Mixed line with fixed anchors.

climbs.name: I'm a Doctor, Not a Climber

content.description:
Mixed route with a bolted slightly bouldery start. Easy protection up top with several horizontal finger/hand cracks. 



First bolted line (3 bolts) on the left of the face. 

Bolted start with Fixed anchors.

Follow the obvious hand crack vertical for twenty feet. Slight traverse left before entering a right overhanging dihedral near the top. 



Vertical crack system located just left of the large overhanging wall. Should be 10 feet left of an osprey next, left of a bolted mixed line. 

Fixed anchors.

Mixed route on thinner features located on the bolted arête. Rejoin the Phasers on Kill trad line after bolt 2, with a slight traverse left before entering an overhanging dihedral near the top. 



Located on the bolted arête between Phasers on Kill and Phasers on Stun trad lines. 

Two bolts and fixed anchors.

A juggy start leads into a crack system that widens with elevation. A right curving hand crack sits above a bulge, pull this and continue vertical until under a small roof in a slight dihedral. Head slightly up and very left, traversing across a thin hand crack with precise feet. A quick blast vertical using several horizontal hand cracks now gets you at the anchors. 



Second from the left in the crack riddled wall left of the large overhanging section that is dominated by hard sport climbs. The first trad line right of the bolted start of tipytoe. 

Thin pro down low, but lots after about 12 feet. Fixed anchors shared with tipytoe.

Slightly runout start gives way to some good pro at the base of the v-notch. Continue up the notch into a flared chimney. 



The first climb in Star Trek Sector. Identifiable as a v-notch left of Breakfast Cookie.

No anchors, so walk off or rap on Breakfast Cookie to the right.

A bouldery start for two bolts before traversing hard right for 20 feet along a horizontal finger to hand crack. Place a cam (~0.5) before heading up the face to a nice ledge rest above. A short jug haul left, up then right will get you to the anchor. Very stiff for the grade, especially by Calabogie standards. 



Easy to locate traverse under a large roof. 


3 bolts and fixed anchors.
Named after old Star Trek themed names.  A cliff of old and new climbs and great popularity.
